Installing Software and data for R workshop (more detailed version)

1. Installing R and RStudio

The first step is to install the R and RStudio applications:

  • Download R @ The R Project’s Home Page
    • Windows
    • Linux
    • Mac

  • Download RStudio Desktop

  • Run the installers for R and RStudio, in that order.

If successful, you should be able to open RStudio and it looks like this.

1b. Trying it out

You can copy-paste this command into the window named Console and hit enter. There should be a plot resulting.

plot(Petal.Length~Sepal.Length, data = iris, col = Species)

2. Installing some useful R packages

Now, run the following command to install a useful collection of packages (you can copy-paste the text below directly into the command prompt in R and hit enter):

install.packages("tidyverse")

Here is a recording of the installation on my own computer. (This installation may take a while)

The tidyverse is a collection of useful packages that add a lot of functionality to what is built-in to R. The two main packages we will use are:

  • dplyr: for filtering, aggregating and summarising data
  • ggplot2: for superior data visualisation

2b. Trying it out

You can verify the tidyverse installed by trying the following:

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length, colour = Species)) + 
  geom_point()

3. Getting data we will be using

Install the data we will be using:

install.packages("devtools")
library(devtools)
install_github("thisisdaryn/workshop")

3b. Trying it out

library(workshop)
head(lara)

3c There’s one remaining package with data that we may be using:

install.packages("nycflights13")
  • This data set contains flight information from 2013 for flights out of the 3 major airports in or near to New York City.
  • You can verify you have the data using the following command
library(nycflights13)
View(flights)
